Regarding the interpretation of the results, we first highlight the significance of jointly modelling the competing risks and longitudinal CKD outcomes. The estimates of the association parameters (the alphas) are significantly different from zero, demonstrating the benefit of using a joint modeling approach for the CKD follow-up data. The negative estimate indicates that there is an inverse relationship between the hazard of experiencing either of the competing failure events (death and/or ESRD) and the longitudinal outcome, log(eGFR). For instance, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\:{\widehat{\alpha\:}}_{E1}-1.76\:\left(HR=0.17,\:95{\%}\:{\text{CI}}:\:0.10,\:\:0.28\right)$$\end{document} indicates that the log-hazard ratio for a unit increase in log(eGFR) was − 1.76. This means that a one-unit increase in log(eGFR) was associated with an 83% decrease (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\:95\%\:CI:\:72\%,\:90\%$$\end{document}) in the hazard of experiencing end-stage renal disease, assuming other covariates are held constant.

